<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECHY ON ROONEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Novelist John Rechy discovered that Andy Rooney, after making his apologies on 
CBS' "60 Minutes" for some loony remarks about gays and blacks, had sustained 
more popularity than President Bush (Op-Ed Page, March 9). So, the USC lecturer 
then set out to prove that Rooney was really a bigot after all, albeit a nice 
one. 
</P>
<P>
The current trend with such matters is that unless you hold solely to a 
politically correct view on race, homosexuality, women's rights, etc., you 
become open to yet another powerful victims lobby and in Rooney's case, 
considerable persecution and nearly the loss of his job. It's thought control 
and repression of the 1950s revisited, only this time perpetrated by many 
college professors and universities. Rooney found out that the only way 
subjects of race or homosexuality can be discussed is through bland inane 
pieties that do little to advance knowledge or understanding. 
</P>
<P>
Rechy makes some missteps of his own. For his purposes, he prefers that the 
option, if you will, of deciding whether you are "straight" or homosexual is 
much like deciding whether you're going to be a Republican or a Democrat. Then 
he corrupts Rooney's positive affirmation of his culture and his life's 
preferences that flow from that as a statement of bigotry with moral 
equivalents about Nazis and white supremacists. How thoughtful! Rooney like 
Rechy added little to the dialogue, but in this instance Rechy made victims of 
us all. 
</P>
<P>
BURTON FREEMAN 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
