<HEADLINE>
<P>
LITHUANIA A CRUCIAL DIFFERENCE; 
</P>
<P>
BALTIC FREEDOM NEEDN'T MAKE THE DOMINOES FALL; 
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW COULD LET ALL THREE BALTIC STATES GO WITHOUT UNLEASHING AN EXODUS FROM 
OTHER REPUBLICS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By WILLIAM PFAFF, William Pfaff is a Times syndicated columnist based in Paris. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There never has been reason for confidence that the Soviet Union would let 
Lithuania secede. There has always been cause to ask if it can let Lithuania 
go. The war of nerves against Lithuania these last few days probably reflects 
indecision and conflict within the Soviet government itself. The choice that 
government finally makes may prove the most important international event since 
reform began in the Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
Moscow understands that if Lithuania secedes, Estonia and Latvia would rapidly 
follow. Disintegrative forces elsewhere would be reinforced. Voters in the 
Ukraine on Sunday gave unexpectedly strong support to republican parliament 
candidates committed to full independence. The Soviet Army seized Lithuanian 
deserters this week because there soon would be no army if servicemen from the 
republics experiencing autonomist agitation were permitted to leave at will. 
Politicians and soldiers nonetheless see that military intervention to prevent 
Lithuania's secession would carry devastating costs. 
</P>
<P>
This is a turning point for Soviet reform, and there is one thing Western 
governments could do that might make a constructive difference: They could 
reemphasize to Moscow that they recognize a crucial distinction between the 
situation of the Baltic republics and that of the other potentially 
secessionist republics and communities. 
</P>
<P>
Stalin's incorporation of the Baltic states into the Soviet Union at the start 
of World War II has never been recognized by the principal Western governments. 
The United States still accords diplomatic recognition to residual elements of 
the prewar republics. France does not recognize the three as legally part of 
the Soviet Union. Britain accords only de facto recognition. 
</P>
<P>
It is different for the Ukraine, Georgia, Azerbaijan, Moldavia and the other 
Soviet republics where autonomist movements have sprung up. Each has a 
complicated relationship with Russia, but none is considered by the Western 
governments as other than a legitimate component of the Soviet Union. Whether 
that status follows from World War II settlement, the civil war that followed 
the 1917 Revolution, or czarist imperial expansion, it is uncontested by the 
Western governments. Secessionist movements in those republics are Soviet 
internal matters. 
</P>
<P>
While the West has supported Baltic independence since the three republics were 
formed in the 1920s, it is not the policy of the Western governments to support 
or advocate the break-up of the Soviet Union itself. In Western eyes, Soviet 
recognition of the Baltics' independence would not establish a precedent. 
</P>
<P>
Precedence is the reason the Balts have presented so terrible a problem to the 
Soviet government. If they are allowed to leave the Soviet Union, where will 
this trend end? The question is fundamental: Disintegrative forces in the 
Soviet Union already are more powerful than anyone among the Soviet reformers 
is likely to have foreseen even two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
Even letting the East European governments go their own ways was supposed to 
produce reform, not revolutionary change in the European system and the 
unification of Germany. Two years ago the belief in Moscow was that new and 
more competent Communist leaders in Eastern Europe could explore economic and 
political solutions the Soviets might adopt. Reforms there were supposed to 
attract Western investment and Western mechanisms of economic dynamism, to the 
Soviet Union's ultimate benefit. In fact, all but Bulgaria and Romania have 
simply gone over to the West. 
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the autonomy already accorded the Baltic states was supposed to 
inspire new economic development and new interactions with the West. The Baltic 
republics were supposed to become the Soviets' "Hong Kong." Instead, they now 
reject autonomy and demand independence. Given independence, they, too, are 
expected to go over to the West. 
</P>
<P>
Two critical issues remain to be settled in the course of Soviet reform. The 
first is this question of autonomy for the component republics of the Soviet 
Union, implying, to those who advocate it, democratic decentralization -- but 
threatening national disintegration. The second is German unification. In 
principle, the Soviet Union seems agreed to Germany's unification. In fact, no 
final accord has been reached as to how this will come about, and Soviet forces 
remain in East Germany. 
</P>
<P>
If Moscow decides to intervene in Lithuania to block independence, Mikhail 
Gorbachev's central European policy still may be challenged in Moscow. There 
certainly are people there who see the re-creation of a united Germany and the 
autonomist movements inside the U.S.S.R. as dual threats to the survival of the 
Soviet Union as a world power. What happens next in Lithuania must seem to them 
a decisive event. They almost certainly are right. 
</P>
</TEXT>
