<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON, D.C.; 
</P>
<P>
HOUSE OKS GARBAGE BAN FOR FOOD TRUCKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The House overwhelmingly passed legislation to ban the hauling of garbage, 
chemicals and hazardous wastes in the same trucks and railroad cars used to 
carry food, beverages and grains. The bill, which is opposed by the Bush 
Administration largely because it would require the Transportation Department 
to assume enforcement responsibility, also states that asbestos, infectious 
waste and other health-threatening items must be shipped only in vehicles 
designated for that purpose. The prime target of the bill, which now goes to 
the Senate, is "backhauling," using trucks that carry food cross-country to 
carry garbage on the trip home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
UNITED STATES -- TRANSPORTATION; TRUCKING INDUSTRY -- UNITED STATES; FOOD 
INDUSTRY -- UNITED STATES; LEGISLATION -- UNITED STATES; FOOD CONTAMINATION AND 
POISONING; RUBBISH COLLECTION; HAZARDOUS MATERIALS; HEALTH HAZARDS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA032890-0084 </DOCNO>
