<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: COSTA MESA; 
</P>
<P>
CHEMICAL SPILLS INTO CANAL AT TIMES PLANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Several gallons of fluid spilled from an air-conditioning unit at The Times 
Orange County plant Tuesday and flowed into storm drains, but the solution 
never reached a drainage canal, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred as a crew was working on rooftop air-conditioning 
equipment at the Sunflower Avenue plant, where three past spills recently 
resulted in $30,000 in fines to the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
Costa Mesa fire officials said that less than five gallons reached a storm 
drain on the newspaper plant's property and that the flow was so minimal that 
it never left Times property. 
</P>
<P>
A Times executive said the spill Tuesday involved the same rust inhibiting 
solution that had been accidentally dumped in storm drains in two of the three 
past incidents. The third spill involved a highly diluted solution of 
developing fluid used in the printing process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<CORRECTION-DATE>
<P>
March 31, 1990, Saturday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</CORRECTION-DATE>
<CORRECTION>
<P>
FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
Chemical spill -- The headline for a story about a chemical spill Tuesday at 
The Times Orange County plant incorrectly said the chemical spilled into a 
canal. As stated in the story, the solution never reached a drainage canal but 
stayed on Times property. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
