<HEADLINE>
<P>
4 FACE RUNOFFS IN SEAL BEACH VOTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SEAL BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The election to fill two open seats on the City Council ended in a draw 
Tuesday, with two candidates who oppose a massive housing development and two 
who favor it headed for a runoff. 
</P>
<P>
Because none of the eight candidates received at least 50% of the vote in 
either of the two council district races, the top two vote-getters in each 
district will appear in a May 8 runoff. 
</P>
<P>
In District 1, which covers the downtown and Surfside neighborhoods, the race 
will pit engineering contractor Joe Rullo against property manager Marilyn 
Bruce Hastings. 
</P>
<P>
In District 3, which covers the Hill neighborhood and part of the Leisure World 
retirement community, Planning Commissioner Gwen Forsythe and environmental 
activist Galen F. Ambrose will face off. 
</P>
<P>
The council seats are being vacated by Joyce Risner and Victor Grgas, two 
members of a council majority that support the Hellman Ranch project proposed 
by the Mola Development Corp. A victory for anti-growth forces in the runoff 
could set up a council majority hostile to the project. 
</P>
<P>
Rullo and Forsythe back the project; Ambrose and Hastings oppose it. 
</P>
<P>
The proposed 329-home Hellman Ranch project was the main issue in the campaign, 
with the eight candidates evenly divided over the issue. 
</P>
<P>
The 149-acre development, which would set aside 41 acres for wetlands 
restoration, was approved by the City Council last October after months of 
often heated debate. 
</P>
<P>
Proponents of the development had hailed the project as being far better than 
the original plan for 773 houses, saying it represented a fair balance between 
commercial and environmental concerns. They insisted that the project would not 
harm Seal Beach, and expressed doubts that the city could keep the owners of 
the land from developing it. 
</P>
<P>
Hellman Ranch foes criticized the plan for not adequately addressing 
environmental concerns. They said they feared that the project would increase 
traffic, pollution and crime, adding that they preferred a plan with fewer 
homes and more wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
The Hellman development took on added importance in the campaign earlier this 
month when an Orange County Superior Court commissioner ruled that the city's 
General Plan was outdated and that the Hellman Ranch development must be 
approved for a second time by the City Council. 
</P>
<P>
Because the General Plan revisions are not final, it is still not known whether 
the council will vote on the measure before May 15, when the two new council 
members will take office. 
</P>
<P>
The election was marked by its lack of rancor and mudslinging in a city known 
for heated politics. 
</P>
<P>
Even with the divisive issue of growth at the forefront, some candidates went 
out of their way not to attack the others directly. 
</P>
<P>
Growth in the city of 26,000 people will be a major issue for the incoming 
council. Two major developments -- one at Bixby Ranch in northern Seal Beach 
and another at a property owned by the Los Angeles Department of Water and 
Power -- will likely be debated by the council in the next year. 
</P>
<P>
Times correspondent Michelle Nicolosi contributed to this story. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
