<HEADLINE>
<P>
FLUOR SUBSIDIARY WINS CONTRACTS IN 3 FOREIGN PROJECTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
IRVINE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fluor Daniel said Tuesday that it has been awarded three contracts involving 
separate construction and energy engineering projects for two foreign companies 
and the government of Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
The company, the principal operating subsidiary of Irvine-based Fluor Corp., 
said it has won contracts to study the possible expansion of a natural gas 
pipeline in Thailand; to supervise construction of a $94-million petrochemical 
plant in England for Royal Dutch Shell Co. of the Netherlands; and to build an 
800,000-square-foot addition to a Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. automobile 
factory in Smyrna, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
Total value of the contracts was not disclosed. But the company said the awards 
added to its contract backlog, which totaled $8.7 billion as of the first 
quarter ended Jan. 31, up 25% from the same period in the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
CONTRACTS; FLUOR DANIEL INC; UNITED STATES -- FOREIGN RELATIONS -- THAILAND; 
UNITED STATES -- FOREIGN RELATIONS -- ENGLAND 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
