<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
FRENCH DECLARE WAR ON TOBACCO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The government declared war on tobacco today, approving a draft law banning all 
cigarette advertising and announcing a 15% increase in the price of tobacco 
products beginning next year. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, advertisements of nearly all alcoholic beverages will be banned 
except in the print media. 
</P>
<P>
The measure will be submitted to Parliament during its spring session, 
government spokesman Louis Le Pensec said. If approved, the bans will be 
implemented progressively over a three-year period. 
</P>
<P>
Most cigarettes now cost between 95 cents and $1.75. The government receives 
about 75% of the revenue from tobacco sales. 
</P>
<P>
Le Pensec said tobacco and alcohol are responsible for 20% of the deaths in 
France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
